<rating>5< /rating>< Text>
Great family-owned, family-friendly confectionery. With roots in Hayward and Castro Valley you will walk down memory lane when you see the pictures of Hayward/Castro Vally's past. Lots of character in the decor and above all else the ice cream and sweets taste amazing. Friendly staff and convenient point of sales checkout that accepts Google Pay. I highly recommend you take a visit.< /Text>

< text>
Ok experience.  Pace of play was good for a Tuesday tee time at 12:20. Check in was efficient and quick.
However, the South course greens were being aerated and there was no advanced disclosure of this condition.  The green roll was therefore pretty poor. That should have been disclosed ahead of time.  Course fairways in East and South only fair.  No drinks for sale out on the course.  Snack bar was efficient.
Oaks North Island a fun (shorter) course for higher handicappers, not real challenging challenging intermediate and above players.< /text>

4.5 stars...Love this great executive course.  They have three different 9 hole courses to choose from when playing a full round.  Prices are affordable and staff is generally friendly and professional. They lost a half star because they failed to return my voicemail from the morning before my pm tee time when I was trying to verify availability of pull carts vs riding carts. Still, no complaints...and I will continue to come back.</Text>

101816280676503821093</user>
<Name>Eve R.< /Name>< date>
1622529847929<//date>
< Rate>
4< /Rate>
< review>
This is a decent used bookstore, but you really need to look to find something good. There aren't many eye catching titles, it's more of an old timey place where you can find the long-forgotten, yellow-paged chapter books you would read back in elementary school.

There are some cool works dating back to 1930s, magic books, conspiracy, war, supernatural, children's books, and many many old romance novels. Their books are in an okay condition, but I think $7 + tax is too steep for their condition. However, they do have a lot of  discounted books for $1 on their sidewalk carts.

The service was good, the older gentleman at the counter was nice and was friendly. He asked if I needed help when I came in and rang me up when I picked out a book. Also, I saw a lady come in with a basket of books, as they also buy from the public. Gold star on that.< /review>

Hand rolls are very worth it, fresh, big, and $4.5 during HH. The Oysters are 1 or 2$ during happy hour but they add sauce on top of them, not necessarily liked the 1$ ones. Sashimi was good but they put a lot of garlic on top of the fish which I don't necessarily love.< /text><Pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOZAXML_v9n5WVKejIsxuDXsR1N9ebdDfMVd6_2=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPMWXR4tCJ03X6UbEtKUgjN7JCMhivIz1dhOA5Y=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO9-wUjEtYs1ETpzw7_v1dkEBAF0qCopztjBQMB=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNoO-0tH-Ofvqvy4LjRAW5NrHk3dXel78z3U_GJ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNTs8oggsBH9M9GM7xR9NTJUHKSBnJnsMoN4Vlj=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOx27VN5Rl3YK_SzVRTVWdU95OlXBee5lAlFLkc=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP7F-ncd2OwAdSiTHweo7MPRRk7v6fKkuRIyp_q=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPi1PsYbGAYhluHPoBTUhV8bK_-l2aIMSKpKvAQ=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNE7F-0_nlT4brYQxdVXeA2GNB5LOBMtAf8sXAg=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPc__jCQ1xWdjPXVPpssNLWmoQ7KTvRbqRCbTm0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN74xsy8UKRj5zdHQCJeaO6PD9vPl38_itc04j5=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]<//Pics>< response>

We love ballpark pizza.   So much nostalgia from this kind of pizza joint when we were kids playing sports.   We also love their pizzas, salad bar, and garlic bread. There are many Union Stations all over the US. While each has its own quality, they all look quite alike in terms of architecture and design style. However, this one is really unique. 1598488855882</date>
<Rating>5</Rating>< review>
The LA Union Station is really nice and luxurious feeling. The high ceilings, chandeliers hanging from the ceiling, and the large leather chairs add to the overall feeling of luxury. It is a safe train station with plenty of food options and its air conditioned. I'd reccomend visiting just for the architecture. They even have a piano where passengers can play and sing to beat the time away during a layover.< /review>

<Name>Lynn P< /Name><review>A huge, classic Art Deco-era railroad station.  Architecture is impressive, and it is used in countless movies and ads.  Metro Stations (Gold, Red, and Purple lines) are within.  A nice lounge upstairs for Business Class-ticket holders for Amtrak trains.  Metrolink also goes out from here, so it's a real transportation hub.  Can also catch buses to LAX, and buses to Dodger Stadium, seasonally.    Fast food establishments are there for a meal or snack plus a sundry-type store.< /review><Time>1581732726857< /Time>< Rating>
5< /Rating>

<Time>1578176141187< /Time>< Text>
What an incredible art deco architecture in this train station!

The moment you enter is like stepping back in time, the atmosphere is lovely here.
What made it even more special was the piano where just a random man was playing beautifully on.

Clear signalization in the station everywhere. Loved being here!<//Text>

<UserId.>111757434573755774154< /UserId.>< user_name>
Heather Tonelli< /user_name>
<time>1595048918872< /time><rating>3</rating>< Text>
This one is hard for me. So I love the station. Beautiful out of this world old school LA. But, try as they might, Amtrak security isn't able to keep all the vagrants from inside the building. I'm constantly getting asked for money, food, ciggs, you name it. A tip though. There is a second lounge upstairs that ticketed business, sleeper and same day passengers can use. You have to show your ticket at the door, but once your in it's really nice. Free drinks and snacks and a TV. Also they have a little museum of sorts up there that shows famous movies that have been made on our in trains and depots with Amtrak. Kinda cool! So if you can, go up there. There's a smoking section outside by where the buses bring you over. There's a dog fake lawn patch for your pets to relieve themselves at out there as well. Lots of security, so your safe everywhere. Make sure you go outside and look at all the beautiful gazebo areas. The architecture at this union station is amazing.< /Text>

It's a beautiful station with british architecture. It's decently connected to the downtown. If you are comming at the night time, u might find homeless people sitting/sleeping in the waiting area, which makes it crowded. Things can get sketchy sometimes at night so try to stay inside the station. Take a trip back in time and be fully in the future. Union Station is a must for every adventurer traveling to southern California.

It is truly the hub of transportation for the city and very accessible.   When you walk through the doors you are instantly taken back to an era when train travel dominated the nation. And this place shows class.

You can easily take a train to all points from this central hub and get to every notable destination in not only the the local area but regionally as well as exploring the country.

Take a weekend up to Santa Barbara or ride the subway to Hollywood.

It's all here.<//Text>

<rating>5< /rating><Review>This place is a cathedral to transportation! The warm lighting and the soothing 'whisper' of all the combined chatter always feels like a welcome home, and i make it a point to get to the station long before my train is boarding, just so i can spend some time in here.  Union Station is a beautiful building to pass through, to wander around, and if you look into the history of it, you'll appreciate it so much more! Their FREE events here, from movie screenings to the train days are so much fun to attend, and although they can get busy, the bathrooms are always open and staffed. I've also had great experiences talking to the officers and people at the information desk, who are always friendly and willing to help. If you can leave the car at home for a day and just take the Metro into this building, you definitely should- it's one of Los Angeles' treasures< /Review><pics>None<//pics><response>None</response><gmapID>0x80c2c737bb90b4cf:0x6a32194f48a74e10</gmapID></record>

A nice old style train station. This place has a lot of history. Amtrak and Metrolink stop here. You can also catch several Metro busses and the Red, Purple, and Gold lines. LAX fly away, and Dodgers shuttles are also here. There's lots of security and police so it's safe. They recently upgraded the restrooms. Amtrak has a Metropolitan lounge for business class, and sleeper car passengers.  Union Station also has several events going on throughout the year.<//Text>

< Text>
An historic building. Lovely structure, well-worn. It's busy. A number of light rail lines terminate here (gold, purple, red lines). Metrolink heavy rail is here too. Amtrak trains also run through the station.

Food choices are pretty dank here.

Definitely take the time to walk the flhalls.< /Text>

105084304650893139598< /user_id>
<user_name>Phillip Pirrip< /user_name><Time>1551386227266<//Time>< rating>
4< /rating>
< Text>
The architecture of the building is pretty awesome to look around for it's historic significance.

There's an assortment of sit down and fast food places to grab something to eat while waiting for your train.

The general area was clean and we'll kept.

There's really no general seating if you're waiting for your train, unless you have a ticket with a departure time within 2 hours.  I'm sure it helps cut down on loitering, but don't know what someone would do if they had a long layover.

Didn't find any power outlets, so that's a have if you need to charge your mobile device.< /Text>

< pics>
None</pics>
<date>1604633701794<//date></record></dataset><record>
< Text>
The primary gateway into and out of LA, via the train.

It's urban, so it has some rough edges. Being focused on getting people in and out, seating is lacking.

If the weather is nice, and when isn't it in Southern California, sit outside near the water agency building. Peaceful old fountains and courtyard will take your mind far from the bustle of LA.

The architecture of the station is beautiful. Pause to appreciate the ambition, craftsmanship, hope, and pride that existed in the 1920s.

Since we're taking the train, slow down. Enjoy the journey.</Text>

FYI, access to the Metropolitan Lounge is right across from the rental car counters and involves a flight of stairs.  After you are in the lounge, no more steps and you will be able to take a ramp to a redcap shuttle (golf cart) that will take you  to your platform.  Great service by all the Amtrak employees I encountered.</Text>

< Review>
Logistical mess to actually get to the airport. Some interesting characters hanging around here too. Trains are frequently delayed or cancelled. Trains run to places maybe once an hour or more - definitely not world class service where trains run to important places every 5-10 minutes (even in some 3rd World countries). Meanwhile, we keep stuffing the highways with more cars that can't move anywhere. Perhaps our decision-makers need to leave the country once in a while to get a clue. Train staff are very professional, but for infrequent or delayed services, completely overpriced. Still a nice change from a commute if you have the time.< /Review>

< rate>
4</rate>
< Text>
It's a gorgeous place for photo ops and ogling. Very close to Olvera st and Chinatown. I understand and appreciate them trying to keep homeless people out, but sectioning off the seats makes one feel like you're in a cattle pen. The Amtrak employees are pretty helpful but the metro ones are 100% done with people and it shows. Theres a great (if a little expensive) coffee shop towards the back of the station, and Starbucks up front if you like long lines. The little market there (used to be famima) is ok but smells like old grease and stinks up the lobby. Great variety of snacks though. Dont bother with the bathrooms. Just hold it til you get on the train.<//Text>

< review>
LA Union Station is a Mission Revival train station that is located just North of Downtown on Alameda and Cesar Chavez Blvd. This is the major terminal for Amtrak service on the West Coast. Metrolink, the local commuter passenger railway also ends here. This is the where both Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Agency Red and Green Lines terminate and Gold Line passes through has a station on Tracks One and Two.< /review>

<Pics>None<//Pics><rate>5<//rate><review>Los Angeles Union Station is an iconic piece of history and a beautiful station. It is the central station for the city and it is here you will find both the Metrolink train system that runs throughout the county of Los Angeles over several lines, and into Ventura, Orange and San Bernardino counties as well. Additionally, the Amtrak trains pass through here as well. The station also is the terminus for the Red and Purple subway lines, and for the Gold line. There are help desks available for all systems, as well as ticketing kiosks and maps. The station is large, filled with beautiful early twentieth century architecture and fittings; the markets and restaurants inside are tastefully fitted into the structure.</review>< Name>
Sean G. Rosenstock</Name>

< review>
(Translated by Google) Union Station is one of Los Angeles's most historic buildings, opened in 1939, and the transcontinental railroad, commonly known as Amtrak, departs from here.
This station is the main station on the west coast and connects to the subway as well as long-distance trains. The east exit is mainly the place where the bus to LAX Airport called "FLY AWAY" leaves, but there is only a roundabout in front of the station and there is nothing else. The west exit should be the gateway to Union Station.
Compared to the terminal stations in Japan, the number of people is small.
Little Tokyo is just south of here.
Just south of it is Skid Row.

(Original)

(Translated by Google) This is the first railway station to be built in Los Angeles. It was created thanks to the collaboration of three of the most important railway companies in California - Union Pacific, Southern Pacific and Archison, Topeka anf Santa Fe Railway. Its opening in May 1939 was accompanied by 3-day celebrations and parades. The building is built in the style of the Spanish Renaissance, there are arches, arcades, wooden decorated ceilings and stucco. Interesting fact - the walls of the building are covered with cork - there is no echo. Waiting room with wonderful leather seats available to holders of a valid train ticket.
In addition to the train station, the station includes underground metro stations, a station and a bus terminus.
